2. REACT QUERY USAGE PATTERNS
================================================================================

FINDINGS:

[HIGH] Excessive console.log in queryClient.ts - Production builds will have
  verbose logging on every API request and response (lines 334, 374, 427, 448,
  464, etc.). This impacts performance and leaks information in production.
  Recommendation: Wrap all debug logs in process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development'.

[MEDIUM] Custom queryFn defined in SelectedProjectContext.tsx (line 63-80)
  bypasses the default query function. The default queryFn already handles auth
  headers and offline fallback, but this custom one manually adds Authorization
  header from localStorage directly instead of using the centralized
  getStoredAccessToken(). This creates inconsistency.

[MEDIUM] Header component (header.tsx line 99-107) defines a custom queryFn
  for projects that also bypasses the default queryFn with its own error handling
  that silently returns empty arrays, potentially masking real errors.

[MEDIUM] queryClient defaults have refetchOnWindowFocus: false,
  refetchOnMount: false, and refetchOnReconnect: false. While this improves
  performance, it means data can become stale without the user realizing it.
  The pull-to-refresh partially mitigates this, but users on desktop have no
  easy way to refresh data other than full page reload.

[LOW] getQueryFn joins queryKey with "/" (line 313): `queryKey.join("/")`.
  This assumes all query keys are path segments, which works for API endpoints
  but could break if non-path query keys are used.

[GOOD] Proper cache invalidation after mutations using queryKey arrays.
[GOOD] Offline fallback with local storage when network is unavailable.
[GOOD] Token refresh retry logic on 401 responses.

