5. AUTHENTICATION FLOW AUDIT
================================================================================

FINDINGS:

[HIGH] Token storage in localStorage (AuthProvider.tsx lines 446-452) - 
  Access tokens and refresh tokens are stored in localStorage, which is
  vulnerable to XSS attacks. Any XSS vulnerability would allow token theft.
  Consider using httpOnly cookies for token storage.

[HIGH] Offline login accepts any locally-stored user if password hash
  verification passes (AuthProvider.tsx lines 290-334). The offline user
  data in IndexedDB could potentially be tampered with if an attacker has
  access to the browser's dev tools. The role from offline storage is trusted
  without server validation.

[MEDIUM] AuthProvider trusts localStorage 'emailVerified' flag (lines 145, 425).
  A user could manually set localStorage.setItem('emailVerified', 'true') to
  bypass email verification checks on the frontend. Backend should enforce this.

[MEDIUM] ProtectedRoute logs sensitive information (user email) to console on
  every render (line 19-25). This should be removed in production.

[MEDIUM] ProtectedRoute has an exclusion list for paths (line 51) that allows
  unauthenticated users to pass through. This is checked via
  window.location.pathname which could potentially be manipulated. However,
  since these routes (/check, /login, etc.) are also defined outside the
  ProtectedRoute wrapper in App.tsx, this is redundant dead code.

[LOW] AdminRoute role check (line 34-35): `adminRoles` is hardcoded as
  ["admin", "super_admin"]. If new admin roles are added, this must be
  updated in multiple places.

[GOOD] Session revalidation on network reconnect (AuthProvider lines 200-252).
[GOOD] Storage event listener for cross-tab logout (lines 189-198).
[GOOD] AbortController with timeout on login request (lines 263-265).

