6. XSS VULNERABILITIES
================================================================================

FINDINGS:

[HIGH] ai-chat.tsx (line 50-53, 83, 92): The `generatePrintPDF` function
  takes AI-generated content, performs regex replacements to create HTML
  (replacing **bold** with <strong> tags, newlines with <br/>), and writes
  it directly to a new window via document.write() WITHOUT sanitization.
  If the AI response contains malicious HTML/JS, it will execute in the
  user's browser context.
  
  Affected code:
    const contentHTML = content
      .replace(/\*\*(.+?)\*\*/g, "<strong>$1</strong>")
      .replace(/━+/g, "<hr/>")
      .replace(/\n/g, "<br/>");
    win.document.write(html);  // html contains unsanitized contentHTML

  Similarly, table data from AI (line 45) is inserted without escaping:
    `<td>${row[c] != null ? String(row[c]) : "-"}</td>`

  Recommendation: Use DOMPurify (already in the project for pdf-exports.tsx)
  to sanitize all AI-generated content before inserting into HTML.

[HIGH] equipment-management.tsx (line 586): document.write with
  potentially unsanitized content in print functionality.

[MEDIUM] main.tsx (line 71): innerHTML used for error display, but the
  content is a hardcoded Arabic string, so XSS risk is minimal here.

[GOOD] pdf-exports.tsx and pdfGenerator.ts properly use DOMPurify for
  HTML sanitization.

[GOOD] React's JSX auto-escaping prevents most XSS in rendered components.

